  <h2>ðŸ”¹ Synopsis: Virtualization</h2>

  <p><strong>Virtualization</strong> is a technology that allows multiple simulated environments or dedicated resources to run on one physical hardware system. This is achieved using a software layer called a <strong>hypervisor</strong>, which manages and isolates <strong>virtual machines (VMs)</strong> or containers.</p>

  <h3>ðŸ”¸ Types of Virtualization:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Hardware Virtualization</strong> â€“ Running multiple VMs on one server.</li>
    <li><strong>Operating System Virtualization</strong> â€“ Using containers like Docker.</li>
    <li><strong>Application Virtualization</strong> â€“ Running apps in isolated environments.</li>
    <li><strong>Desktop Virtualization</strong> â€“ Accessing desktops remotely (e.g., VDI).</li>
    <li><strong>Storage Virtualization</strong> â€“ Combining multiple storage devices into one.</li>
    <li><strong>Network Virtualization</strong> â€“ Creating virtual networks over physical ones.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>ðŸ”¸ Benefits:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Cost savings</li>
    <li>Efficient resource utilization</li>
    <li>Scalable and flexible infrastructure</li>
    <li>Easier disaster recovery</li>
    <li>Safer testing environments</li>
    <li>Enhanced portability and security</li>
  </ul>

